DESCRIPTION_3: Will post on Facebook for comment - PLEASE comment!  On the corner of Wesley and Hillgirt Circle, Oakland, is a section of overgrown bushes, aloes and small trees which has grown overarching the sidewalk (from street side) and into the sidewalk from the homeowner's fence, impeding visibility ESPECIALLY in the darkness.  It is a dangerous and unlighted section of sidewalk.  At least one person was attacked in this location (my daughter).  Passers by avoid this section of the block and for good reason, walking in the street instead which is not safe either.  The bushes are so thick that a person could step back into them and be completely concealed from view.  There is no streelight.  The homeowners have declined to maintain the area outside their fence.  As you can see from the photos, the area is very overgrown and impinging on the sidewalk.  Imagine the person in the photograph dressed in black, at night.  The Feet on the Street neighborhood lighting patrol group has observed this area; the entire neighborhood deems it to be unsafe; it was reported to public works last year by Hoang Banh, our Community Rep from OPD; neighbors on the Cleveland Heights Neighbors email group addressed the homeowners who have advised pedestrians "cross the street and walk there".  FOS members attempted to petition the city for a streelight (1.5 years ago) but funding ran out before the petition was processed.  Thank you for your attention.  UPDATE:  PARTIAL IMPROVEMENT BY HOMEOWNERS - THERE STILL NEEDS TO BE WORK DONE BY REMOVAL OF LARGE PINE TREES (NOT ALL PERHAPS EVERY OTHER ONE), ADDITIONAL STREET LIGHT, AND REMOVAL OF OVERGROWTH FROM YARD OVER SIDEWALK TO STREET.

DESCRIPTION_4:
Over the last several years a vandal or vandals has damaged many of the newly planted trees along Lake Merritt Blvd between Oak Street and E 12th Street. Many of these trees have had numerous branches torn off or had the entire trunk broken off a few feet above the ground.

Many of the trees in this area have had their support poles and ties removed. Today's strong winds are now blowing over some of these trees. It appears that several of the trees in the median on Lake Merritt Blvd between 12th Street and 13th Street are very close to falling entirely into the adjacent traffic lanes.
DESCRIPTION_5:
A tree in Peralta Park just past the east end of the Kaiser Convention Center parking lot has very low hanging branches around 80% of the tree that reach to the ground and create a nearly closed off space.

Since the homeless campers were removed from their campsite under this tree groups of kids have been using this area as a gathering place and for illegal drug use. Recently these groups have grown much larger and more agressive toward pedestrians using the sidewalk along the east edge of this parking lot.

Please consider trimming back all low branches to at least head height all the way around this tee. This would make activity beneath the tree much more visible, would likely cause these large groups to disperse, and would increase pedestrian safety in this area.

DESCRIPTION_3: Two trees blew over in heavy winds earlier this week.  One in front of Cana and the other in front of Lane Splitter Pizza.  Both have been removed -- leaving vacant steel tree grates.  These trees were installed barely over a year ago by an outside contractor.  The root ball was obviously not placed deep enough and the trees weren't adequately staked.  What was a beautiful to the streetscape is now an eyesore and potentially hazardous.  Please note that I'm filing a separate complaint about a tree around the corner that was damaged under similar circumstances.
DESCRIPTION_4: downed, broken tree
DESCRIPTION_5: This is one of about 10 street trees that were planted just over a year ago as part of the Lakeshore Complete Streets Improvement Project.  Three have already fallen and been removed.  At least three others have snapped off part way up the trunk including one on Rand that's two-thirds gone.  This can't be coincidental.  Blame has to go to the contractors who installed the trees without adequate staking and most likely too shallow with too little soil compaction.  The trees need to be replaced.  It would be nice to see it done at the contractor's expense - not the city's.

DESCRIPTION_0: Dead pine tree at Lake Merritt, opposite 1400 Lakeshore Ave.
DESCRIPTION_1: Dead pine tree next to Lake Merritt, opposite 1330 Lakeshore Ave.
DESCRIPTION_2:
Over the last several years a vandal or vandals has damaged many of the newly planted trees along Lake Merritt Blvd between Oak Street and E 12th Street. Many of these trees have had numerous branches torn off or had the entire trunk broken off a few feet above the ground.

Many of the trees in this area have had their support poles and ties removed. Today's strong winds are now blowing over some of these trees. It appears that several of the trees in the median on Lake Merritt Blvd between 12th Street and 13th Street are very close to falling entirely into the adjacent traffic lanes.
DESCRIPTION_3:
A tree in Peralta Park just past the east end of the Kaiser Convention Center parking lot has very low hanging branches around 80% of the tree that reach to the ground and create a nearly closed off space.

Since the homeless campers were removed from their campsite under this tree groups of kids have been using this area as a gathering place and for illegal drug use. Recently these groups have grown much larger and more agressive toward pedestrians using the sidewalk along the east edge of this parking lot.

Please consider trimming back all low branches to at least head height all the way around this tee. This would make activity beneath the tree much more visible, would likely cause these large groups to disperse, and would increase pedestrian safety in this area.
DESCRIPTION_4: Someone has been vandalizing the newly planted trees and shrubs along Lake Merrit Blvd between Oak St and E 12 St. Many trees have had their supports damaged or removed and/or have had branches broken or removed. Some of the trees on the south side of Lake Merrit Blvd have had their trunks broken off below all lateral branches leaving only bare trunks. Many shrubs from the Lake Merrit Blvd median have been uprooted and left on the sidewalks. The most damage seems to occur over the weekends.
DESCRIPTION_5:
After years of watching the new street trees along Lake Merritt Boulevard be vandalized I think I finally spotted the culprit.

As of 3:25 PM today he was walking eastbound on the north side of Lake Merritt Boulevard ripping branches off the trees near the intersection with 12th Street.

He appears to be the longest term homeless camper in the Lake Merritt Boulevard area. His campsite has most recently been at the very southernmost end of the underpass walkway (west side of the channel) that connects the lakeshore path with Peralta Park.

Male, approx. 50 years old, approx. 6 feet tall, Black, partly balding. I would not be surprised if this single individual was entirely responsible for the damage and destruction of dozens of trees and shrubs in this area over the last few years.

DESCRIPTION_1:
A tree in Peralta Park just past the east end of the Kaiser Convention Center parking lot has very low hanging branches around 80% of the tree that reach to the ground and create a nearly closed off space.

Since the homeless campers were removed from their campsite under this tree groups of kids have been using this area as a gathering place and for illegal drug use. Recently these groups have grown much larger and more agressive toward pedestrians using the sidewalk along the east edge of this parking lot.

Please consider trimming back all low branches to at least head height all the way around this tee. This would make activity beneath the tree much more visible, would likely cause these large groups to disperse, and would increase pedestrian safety in this area.

When It happened again today, there was no significant wind.

DESCRIPTION_3:
Over the last several years a vandal or vandals has damaged many of the newly planted trees along Lake Merritt Blvd between Oak Street and E 12th Street. Many of these trees have had numerous branches torn off or had the entire trunk broken off a few feet above the ground.

Many of the trees in this area have had their support poles and ties removed. Today's strong winds are now blowing over some of these trees. It appears that several of the trees in the median on Lake Merritt Blvd between 12th Street and 13th Street are very close to falling entirely into the adjacent traffic lanes.
DESCRIPTION_4:
A tree in Peralta Park just past the east end of the Kaiser Convention Center parking lot has very low hanging branches around 80% of the tree that reach to the ground and create a nearly closed off space.

Since the homeless campers were removed from their campsite under this tree groups of kids have been using this area as a gathering place and for illegal drug use. Recently these groups have grown much larger and more agressive toward pedestrians using the sidewalk along the east edge of this parking lot.

Please consider trimming back all low branches to at least head height all the way around this tee. This would make activity beneath the tree much more visible, would likely cause these large groups to disperse, and would increase pedestrian safety in this area.

What was a beautiful to the streetscape is now an eyesore and potentially hazardous.  Please note that I'm filing a separate complaint about a tree around the corner that was damaged under similar circumstances.

DESCRIPTION_5: This is one of about 10 street trees that were planted just over a year ago as part of the Lakeshore Complete Streets Improvement Project.  Three have already fallen and been removed.  At least three others have snapped off part way up the trunk including one on Rand that's two-thirds gone.  This can't be coincidental.  Blame has to go to the contractors who installed the trees without adequate staking and most likely too shallow with too little soil compaction.  The trees need to be replaced. DESCRIPTION_0:
Over the last several years a vandal or vandals has damaged many of the newly planted trees along Lake Merritt Blvd between Oak Street and E 12th Street. Many of these trees have had numerous branches torn off or had the entire trunk broken off a few feet above the ground.

Many of the trees in this area have had their support poles and ties removed. Today's strong winds are now blowing over some of these trees. It appears that several of the trees in the median on Lake Merritt Blvd between 12th Street and 13th Street are very close to falling entirely into the adjacent traffic lanes.
DESCRIPTION_1:
A tree in Peralta Park just past the east end of the Kaiser Convention Center parking lot has very low hanging branches around 80% of the tree that reach to the ground and create a nearly closed off space.

Since the homeless campers were removed from their campsite under this tree groups of kids have been using this area as a gathering place and for illegal drug use. Recently these groups have grown much larger and more agressive toward pedestrians using the sidewalk along the east edge of this parking lot.

Please consider trimming back all low branches to at least head height all the way around this tee. This would make activity beneath the tree much more visible, would likely cause these large groups to disperse, and would increase pedestrian safety in this area.
DESCRIPTION_2: Resident complains of trees & shrubs block vision at the intersection of College and Oakland
DESCRIPTION_3:
After years of watching the new street trees along Lake Merritt Boulevard be vandalized I think I finally spotted the culprit.

As of 3:25 PM today he was walking eastbound on the north side of Lake Merritt Boulevard ripping branches off the trees near the intersection with 12th Street.

He appears to be the longest term homeless camper in the Lake Merritt Boulevard area. His campsite has most recently been at the very southernmost end of the underpass walkway (west side of the channel) that connects the lakeshore path with Peralta Park.

Male, approx. 50 years old, approx. 6 feet tall, Black, partly balding. I would not be surprised if this single individual was entirely responsible for the damage and destruction of dozens of trees and shrubs in this area over the last few years.

DESCRIPTION_5:
Two dead pine trees on property. Mitch Thomson is investigating tree closed to the street, as it may be a hazard to public right of way. Requesting that you investigate tree #2, possible threat to 93 Maggiora Dr. 
Per Mitch Thomson:
	The tree that is closest to the street may be considered a threat to the public street.  Ill check the tree in the field and confirm whether or not it is considered a threat.  If it is a threat, it is a violation of Chapter 12.32 of the Oakland Municipal Code, Street Trees and Shrubs.  Tree Services administers 12.32 OMC; well put the owner on notice to remove the tree.
 	The other tree, the one that could fall on private property, is a violation of Chapter 8.24 OMC, Property Blight.  Dead trees are included in the definition of blight, and are not allowed on private property.  The Blight Ordinance is administered by Building Services.  Contact them and it will be assigned to a building inspector for follow-up.  Your contact is Ayanna Meekins, Public Service Representative, Department of Planning and Building, (510)238-6216, ameekins@oaklandnet.com

This is a 2nd request as the tree is still  leaning off the slope over Sanborn Dr.  See Issue ID: 1507081 /Svc Rqt  ID: 569240  archive.   City of Oakland Pub Wk.s closed the issue on Apr 16, --the tree taken down was a tall dead cypress from comment 3, which by the way was removed along with a lot of other blue paint dabbed trees that needed to come out - all in all a big job.   However I guess I need to write again, that an acacia tree is leaning out towards Sanborn Drive  dragging into a lower tree - Live Oak--,  and one of these days falling onto the roadway.  It's not marked  so I can put small color penants at the trunk -- to make sure you see it.  
On Sanbn Dr  past the yellow gate, where there's a road divide and  Keep Right sign,  go down left side [northwest]35 paces or so,  and look up hill past some other trees.  " tree is 20,30 degrees from vertical, 18 - 20 inches diameter, one branch has torn off about 10 ft up, [late Jan / early Feb] the tree reaches down into a live oak and the last third of its height leans over into the road, . Also there's native plants on that hillside like lupine, purple needlegrass, yarrow, live oak bay laurel, and note that near the base of that tree is a little poison oak 2feet away and 9 10 feet away.[just so you don't get the rash]
It's a problem tree -- going to be more troubling. "
Friends of Sausal Crk  does some volunteer broom and acacia cutting.  Our Field coordinator says this one is too big too crooked and to look around for help.   Will you please check it out and tell us what you think about  removing it.       Thank you.       Alan  Tong

At least three others have snapped off part way up the trunk including one on Rand that's two-thirds gone.  This can't be coincidental.  Blame has to go to the contractors who installed the trees without adequate staking and most likely too shallow with too little soil compaction.  The trees need to be replaced.  It would be nice to see it done at the contractor's expense - not the city's.
